newsitem.title: USA: NYMEX electricity futures end mixed, PV higher.
newsitem.headline: NYMEX electricity futures end mixed, PV higher.

text.p: NYMEX electricity futures ended mixed in a relatively quiet session with California-Oregon Border (COB) front months lower on some early profit taking, industry sources said.
"COB was bid lower early in the day, and then it was pretty stagnant," said one New York-based futures broker.
September COB ended down 15 cents at $18.71 from trade as high as $19.25, while October ended down nine cents at $16.71 from trade as high as $17.10.
Remaining COB deferreds closed steady to five cents higher.
September Palo Verde (PV) settled up 65 cents at $21.60 from trade in a range of $20.90-21.70, while October, though untraded, settled 30 cents higher at $17.05.
Most remaining PV deferreds settled 20-30 cents higher, with the exception of August, 1997, which ended down five cents at $23.20.
NYMEX said an estimated 119 COB contracts and 89 PV contracts traded.
-- Chris Reese, New York Power Desk 212-859-1627
